NAME - ::<namespace>:: emulation_dhcp_config

DESCRIPTION

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT, IxNetwork-NGPF

Configures DHCP emulation for the specified test port or handle.

SYNOPSIS - ::<namespace>::emulation_dhcp_config

List arguments in the alphabetical order or in the reverse alphabetical order.

ARGUMENTS

[M] indicates if the argument is mandatory on the supported platform.

-handle

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

Specifies the handle of the port upon which emulation is configured.Mandatory for the mode -modify. Valid for -version ixtclhal, ixnetwork.

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

Specifies the handle of the port upon which emulation is configured. Mandatory for the mode -modify. Valid for -version ixtclhal, ixnetwork. When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology.

DEFAULT

 None

-mode

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork [M] , IxOS/IxNetwork-FT [M]

DESCRIPTION

This option defines the action to be taken on the port specified by the port_handle argument. Valid for -version ixtclhal, ixnetwork.

Valid options are:

create

Creates an DHCP session, requires the use of -port_handle.

modify

Modifies an DHCP session, requires the use of -handle.

reset

Stops the emulation locally without attempting to clear the bound address from the DHCP server.

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

This option defines the action to be taken on the port specified by the port_handle argument. Valid for -version ixtclhal, ixnetwork.

Valid options are:

create

Creates an DHCP session, requires the use of -port_handle.

modify

Modifies an DHCP session, requires the use of -handle.

reset

Stops the emulation locally without attempting to clear the bound address from the DHCP server.

DEFAULT

create

-outstanding_session_count

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork

DESCRIPTION

Specifies the maximum number of outstanding sessions (unacknowledged discover or request message) allowed to exist. In effect, this is a rate limiting mechanism that stops dhcp servers from being overwhelmed with reqests. Valid for -version ixnetwork.

DEFAULT

50

DESCRIPTION

Specifies the maximum number of outstanding sessions (unacknowledged discover or request message) allowed to exist. In effect, this is a rate limiting mechanism that stops dhcp servers from being overwhelmed with reqests. Valid for -version ixnetwork.

DEFAULT

50

-no_write

Supported platforms Details

IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

If this option is present, the configuration is not written to the hardware. This option can be used to queue up multiple configurations before writing to the hardware. Writing the configurations to hardware can be done only once in the ::::emulation_dhcp_group_config, if you want to modify you have to redo the configurations and write them again. Valid for -version ixtclhal.

DEFAULT

 None

-reset

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

Clears the hardware. If mode is "create" and the reset parameter is present, all the configurations will be erased from memory and the new config is created using the new given parameters. If mode is "create" and the reset parameter is not present, a new session is added in the local array. If mode is "modify" or "reset", the -reset parameter cannot be used. Valid for -version ixtclhal, ixnetwork.

DEFAULT

 None

When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology.

When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology.

mode

Supported platforms Details

DESCRIPTION

This option defines the action to be taken on the port specified by the port_handle argument. Valid for -version ixtclhal, ixnetwork.

Valid options are:

create

Creates an DHCP session, requires the use of -port_handle.

modify

Modifies an DHCP session, requires the use of -handle.

reset

Stops the emulation locally without attempting to clear the bound address from the DHCP server.

IxNetwork-NGPF

When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology.
